var tafsirData_30 = {
  1: {
    "Alif-Lãm-Mĩm": "These are disconnected letters (Huroof Muqatta'at) that appear at the beginning of some Surahs in the Quran. Their exact meaning is known only to Allah. Some scholars say they serve to capture attention and demonstrate that the Quran, though composed of such letters, is a miraculous book that no human can replicate. These letters remind us that while we understand much of the Quran, there are aspects of divine knowledge that remain beyond human comprehension."
  },
  2: {
    "The Romans have been defeated": "This refers to the Byzantine Roman Empire, which was a Christian nation. At the time of this revelation, the Persian Empire (who were fire-worshippers) had defeated the Romans in a major battle. The Meccan pagans rejoiced at this news because they felt a kinship with the Persians, as both were not 'People of the Book.' Meanwhile, the Muslims were saddened because the Romans were closer to them religiously as believers in one God. This verse acknowledges that defeat as a historical fact while setting up a remarkable prophecy."
  },
  3: {
    "in a nearby land": "This refers to the region of Syria and Palestine, which was geographically close to the Arabian Peninsula where the revelation was taking place. Remarkably, modern science has discovered that this area near the Dead Sea is actually the lowest point on Earth's surface, making the phrase 'nearby land' carry both geographical and scientific significance.",
    "Yet following their defeat, they will triumph": "This is a bold divine prophecy. Allah declares that despite the crushing defeat the Romans had just suffered, they would soon rise again and defeat the very Persians who had conquered them. At the time of this revelation, such a prediction seemed highly improbable given how decisively the Romans had been beaten. The Meccan pagans mocked this prophecy, but it served as a test of faith for the believers."
  },
  4: {
    "within three to nine years": "The Arabic word 'bid' refers to a number between three and nine. Allah specified this timeframe for the Roman victory. True to this prophecy, the Romans defeated the Persians within approximately seven years. Abu Bakr (may Allah be pleased with him) even made a wager with the Meccan pagans based on this prophecy, and he won. This precise fulfillment of the prophecy demonstrated the truth of the Quran as divine revelation.",
    "The whole matter rests with Allah before and after victory": "All affairs, all outcomes, and all events are entirely in Allah's control. Victory and defeat, rise and fall of nations—everything happens by Allah's decree. Before the Romans were defeated and after their coming victory, Allah was and remains the one who decides all matters. No empire rises or falls except by His will.",
    "And on that day the believers will rejoice": "When the Romans would achieve their prophesied victory, the Muslims would have reason to celebrate. This is because the victory of people closer to monotheism over idol-worshippers was good news. Additionally, this prophecy's fulfillment would strengthen the believers' faith and prove the truthfulness of the Quran to the doubters."
  },
  5: {
    "at the victory willed by Allah": "The believers' joy would be because this victory came from Allah Himself. It was not merely a military or political outcome but a manifestation of divine will and a confirmation of Quranic prophecy. When Allah grants victory, it carries meaning beyond the battlefield.",
    "He gives victory to whoever He wills": "Allah alone determines who wins and who loses among nations and individuals. Victory is not simply about military strength or resources; it is ultimately granted by Allah to whomever He chooses based on His infinite wisdom. This teaches us that while we must make efforts, the outcome belongs to Allah.",
    "For He is the Almighty, Most Merciful": "Allah possesses absolute power (Al-Aziz) to grant victory to any party He wishes, and none can resist His decree. Yet He is also Most Merciful (Ar-Raheem), meaning His decisions are not arbitrary but guided by wisdom and mercy. He may grant victory to teach lessons, fulfill promises, or show mercy to His servants."
  },
  6: {
    "This is the promise of Allah": "What has been stated about the Roman victory is not mere speculation or wishful thinking—it is a firm promise from the Creator of the heavens and earth. When Allah makes a promise, it is as certain as if it has already happened.",
    "And Allah never fails in His promise": "Unlike human beings who may break their promises due to weakness, forgetfulness, or changing circumstances, Allah never breaks His word. His promises regarding this world and the Hereafter are absolutely guaranteed. This principle applies to all of Allah's promises: rewards for the righteous, punishment for the wicked, and support for the believers.",
    "But most people do not know": "The majority of humanity lacks true understanding of Allah's power and the certainty of His promises. They judge matters only by what they see with their eyes, unable to comprehend divine wisdom and decree. This ignorance leads them to doubt Allah's promises and remain spiritually blind to the truth."
  },
  7: {
    "They only know the worldly affairs of this life": "Most people are experts in worldly matters—business, technology, entertainment, politics, and material pursuits. They understand how to accumulate wealth, gain power, and enjoy pleasures. Their knowledge is limited to the surface of this temporary existence, the things that can be seen, touched, and measured.",
    "but are totally oblivious to the Hereafter": "Despite their worldly intelligence, they are completely heedless and negligent about the eternal life to come. They live as if death will never arrive, as if there will be no resurrection, no accountability, no Paradise or Hell. This tragic imbalance—mastering the temporary while ignoring the permanent—is the greatest loss a person can suffer. True knowledge combines understanding of this world with awareness of the next."
  },
  8: {
    "Have they not reflected upon their own being?": "This is a powerful invitation to self-reflection. Have people not pondered how they were created? How they developed from a drop of fluid into complex beings with intellect, emotions, and purpose? The human body itself—with its intricate systems, senses, and abilities—is evidence of a Creator. If they would simply think deeply about themselves, they would recognize Allah's existence and power.",
    "Allah only created the heavens and the earth and everything in between for a purpose": "Nothing in creation is random, accidental, or meaningless. Every star, every creature, every atom exists for a reason. The universe operates with precision and purpose. This purposeful creation points to a Creator with wisdom and intention. If the creation has purpose, then human life must also have purpose—to worship Allah and prepare for the meeting with Him.",
    "and an appointed term": "Everything in existence has a fixed lifespan determined by Allah. The heavens and earth themselves will one day come to an end on the Day of Judgment. Every individual has their appointed time of death. Nothing lasts forever in this world. This should motivate people to use their limited time wisely.",
    "Yet most people are truly in denial of the meeting with their Lord!": "Despite the clear signs pointing to Allah and the logic of accountability, most humans reject or ignore the reality that they will meet their Creator. They live in denial, either explicitly disbelieving or practically ignoring this inevitable meeting through their heedless lifestyles. This denial is the root of their spiritual problem."
  },
  9: {
    "Have they not travelled throughout the land to see what was the end of those destroyed before them?": "Allah invites the Meccan disbelievers and all humanity to travel and observe the ruins of previous civilizations. The remains of 'Ad, Thamud, the people of Lot, and Pharaoh's Egypt were visible to the Arabs through their trade journeys. These ruins tell a story: powerful nations that rejected their prophets were utterly destroyed. Travel and historical awareness should lead to wisdom and humility.",
    "They were far superior in might": "Those ancient peoples were stronger than the Meccan disbelievers. They had greater armies, more resources, and more advanced capabilities. The people of 'Ad, for example, were known for their enormous physical strength. Pharaoh commanded the mightiest empire of his time. Yet their power did not save them from Allah's punishment. This serves as a warning: if greater nations could not escape divine justice, how can anyone feel safe in their arrogance?",
    "they cultivated the land and developed it more than these Meccans ever have": "Those previous civilizations achieved remarkable progress in agriculture, architecture, and development. They built impressive structures, developed the land extensively, and created flourishing societies that exceeded what the Meccans had accomplished. Yet all their achievements could not protect them when they rejected Allah's guidance. Material progress without spiritual guidance leads to destruction.",
    "Their messengers came to them with clear proofs": "Allah sent every nation a messenger with unmistakable evidence and guidance. These prophets brought miracles, logical arguments, and clear teachings. No nation was destroyed without first receiving divine warning through a prophet. The message was made clear, and they had every opportunity to accept the truth.",
    "Allah would have never wronged them": "Allah is perfectly just. He does not punish people arbitrarily or unfairly. He does not hold people accountable for what they did not know or could not understand. Every punishment that befell previous nations was deserved and proportionate to their crimes of disbelief and injustice.",
    "but it was they who wronged themselves": "By rejecting the truth, persisting in disbelief, and committing sins, those nations brought destruction upon themselves. They were their own worst enemies. Allah gave them guidance, but they chose misguidance. This principle applies universally: when we disobey Allah, we harm ourselves first and foremost."
  },
  10: {
    "Then most evil was the end of the evildoers": "The ultimate fate of those who persisted in wrongdoing was the worst possible outcome. In this world, they faced destruction, humiliation, and erasure. In the Hereafter, they will face eternal punishment in Hellfire. Their end serves as a permanent lesson and warning for all future generations.",
    "for denying and mocking the signs of Allah": "Their crime was twofold: they rejected Allah's clear signs and proofs, and they went further by ridiculing them. They made fun of the prophets, laughed at the message, and treated divine guidance as a joke. This combination of denial and mockery represents the height of arrogance and ingratitude. Those who mock Allah's signs today should take heed of what happened to those who did so in the past."
  },
  11: {
    "It is Allah Who originates the creation": "Allah alone brought all of existence into being from nothing. Before anything existed, He created the heavens, earth, angels, humans, and everything else. This original act of creation demonstrates His absolute power. The One who created from nothing the first time certainly has the ability to do it again.",
    "and will resurrect it": "After death and decay, Allah will bring all creation back to life. Just as He initiated creation, He will repeat it for the Day of Judgment. The resurrection is not difficult for Allah; in fact, it is even easier than the original creation, as mentioned elsewhere in the Quran. Those who doubt the resurrection fail to appreciate the power of the One who created them initially.",
    "And then to Him you will all be returned": "Every single being will return to Allah for judgment. There is no escape, no alternative, and no exception. This return is the ultimate reality that every person must prepare for. Our entire lives are a journey back to our Creator, and how we live determines how that meeting will go."
  },
  12: {
    "On the Day the Hour will arrive": "The Hour refers to the Day of Judgment, which will come suddenly when people least expect it. It is called 'the Hour' because it will come quickly and because of its tremendous significance. On that Day, all the realities that people denied or ignored will become undeniably manifest.",
    "the wicked will be dumbstruck": "The criminals—those who committed sins, rejected truth, and lived in disobedience—will be utterly speechless and paralyzed with despair. The Arabic word 'yublis' implies complete hopelessness and the loss of all ability to respond or defend oneself. All their excuses, arguments, and denials will fail them. The reality they mocked will be right before their eyes, and they will have nothing to say."
  },
  13: {
    "There will be no intercessors for them from among their associate-gods": "All the false gods, idols, saints, and beings they worshipped besides Allah will be completely useless on that Day. They hoped these partners would help them, advocate for them, or protect them from punishment, but none of this will happen. Their so-called intercessors will either be powerless creatures themselves or will completely disown their worshippers. Only intercession that Allah permits will be accepted, and He does not permit intercession for those who died upon shirk (associating partners with Allah).",
    "and they will totally deny their associate-gods": "On that Day, the disbelievers will completely reject and disassociate from the false deities they once worshipped. They will realize that their worship was entirely misplaced and will wish to distance themselves from their former gods. But this belated rejection will not help them, as they spent their lives devoted to falsehood. The very things they worshipped will also deny any relationship with them."
  },
  14: {
    "And on the Day the Hour will arrive": "Again, the Quran emphasizes that the Day of Judgment is a certainty that will definitely come. Repetition of this phrase throughout the Surah serves to drive home the reality that everyone must face.",
    "the people will then be split into two groups": "On that Day, all of humanity will be divided into just two categories—no middle ground, no gray area, no third option. You will either be among the successful believers or among the failed disbelievers. All the complex divisions of this world—nationality, ethnicity, social class, political affiliation—will become meaningless. The only distinction that matters will be faith and deeds."
  },
  15: {
    "As for those who believed and did good": "The first group consists of people who combined correct belief with righteous actions. Faith alone without deeds is incomplete, and deeds without proper faith lack foundation. These successful ones accepted Allah as their Lord, believed in His messengers and revelations, and demonstrated their faith through obedience, worship, and good character. They strove to please Allah throughout their lives.",
    "they will be rejoicing in a Garden": "These blessed people will be celebrating in Paradise (Jannah), described here as a beautiful garden (rawdah). The Arabic word 'yuhbarun' indicates the ultimate happiness, joy, and delight. They will experience pleasure in every form—beautiful surroundings, peace of heart, reunion with loved ones, and the ultimate pleasure of seeing Allah and knowing He is pleased with them. All the struggles and patience of worldly life will be infinitely rewarded."
  },
  16: {
    "And as for those who disbelieved": "The second group consists of those who rejected faith in Allah, His messengers, and His guidance. They chose to deny the truth despite clear evidence.",
    "and denied Our signs and the meeting with Allah in the Hereafter": "Their disbelief manifested in two ways: rejecting Allah's signs (the Quran, prophets, miracles, and evidence in creation) and denying that they would ever meet Allah for judgment. They lived as if there would be no accountability, no resurrection, and no eternal consequences.",
    "they will be confined in punishment": "These people will be brought forcefully into punishment and kept there. The word 'muhdarun' indicates being presented or brought forward, suggesting they will have no choice and no escape. Unlike the believers who enter Paradise happily, these will be dragged into their punishment against their will, where they will remain forever."
  },
  17: {
    "So glorify Allah in the evening": "Declare Allah's perfection, praise Him, and perform prayer when evening comes. This refers to the Maghrib (sunset) and Isha (night) prayers. 'Glorifying Allah' (tasbih) means declaring Him free from any deficiency or partner, recognizing His absolute perfection.",
    "and in the morning": "Similarly, glorify Allah when morning arrives, which refers to the Fajr (dawn) prayer. The day should begin with remembrance of Allah, setting the spiritual tone for everything that follows. The Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him) emphasized that the Fajr prayer is witnessed by angels and carries special blessings."
  },
  18: {
    "all praise is for Him in the heavens and the earth": "Everything in existence—in the heavens and on earth—praises Allah. The angels glorify Him constantly, the creation testifies to His greatness, and believers join this universal chorus of praise. Allah deserves all praise at all times and in all places.",
    "as well as in the afternoon": "This refers to the Asr (afternoon) prayer, performed when the day is progressing toward its end. The Prophet (peace be upon him) said that the one who misses the Asr prayer is as if he lost his family and wealth, highlighting its importance.",
    "and at noon": "This refers to the Dhuhr (midday) prayer, performed when the sun passes its zenith. Thus, these two verses encompass all five daily prayers: Fajr (morning), Dhuhr (noon), Asr (afternoon), Maghrib (evening), and Isha (night). The believer's day is structured around these prayers, maintaining constant connection with Allah from dawn to night."
  },
  19: {
    "He brings forth the living from the dead": "Allah produces living beings from lifeless matter. A living bird emerges from a lifeless egg. A living human develops from a lifeless drop of fluid. A living plant grows from a seemingly dead seed. This miracle happens constantly around us, yet we often fail to appreciate it. Allah alone has the power to create life from non-life.",
    "and the dead from the living": "Similarly, Allah brings forth dead matter from living things. A lifeless egg comes from a living bird. The dead body emerges from what was once a living person. This cycle of life and death is entirely in Allah's control. Scientists can observe these processes but cannot truly create life or fully understand its essence—this remains in Allah's hands.",
    "And He gives life to the earth after its death": "After dry, barren seasons when the land appears completely dead, Allah sends rain and suddenly the earth springs to life with vegetation. This annual transformation is visible proof of Allah's power to resurrect. If He can bring a dead land back to life so easily, resurrecting dead bodies is certainly not difficult for Him.",
    "And so will you be brought forth from the grave": "Just as Allah revives the dead earth, He will resurrect humans from their graves on the Day of Judgment. This is the clear connection: what you witness in nature is a preview and proof of what will happen to you. The One who does this every season with the earth will do the same with human beings when the appointed time comes."
  },
  20: {
    "One of His signs is that He created you from dust": "Allah begins listing His signs that prove His existence, power, and wisdom. The first sign is human creation. Adam, the father of humanity, was created from dust and clay. Every human since then also originates from the earth, as the food that becomes our bodies ultimately comes from the ground. From such humble, lifeless material, Allah created the sophisticated human being.",
    "then—behold!—you are human beings spreading over the earth": "Look at the remarkable result! From mere dust emerged conscious, intelligent, emotional beings who have filled the earth with civilizations, families, and activities. The word 'behold' (idha) expresses amazement at this transformation. Billions of humans now populate the planet, all traced back to that original creation from earth. This should fill us with gratitude and humility toward our Creator."
  },
  21: {
    "And one of His signs is that He created for you spouses from among yourselves": "Allah designed human beings in pairs and created Eve from Adam, making spouses from the same human species. This compatibility is a divine gift. Spouses understand each other because they share the same nature. This pairing is not accidental but a deliberate sign of Allah's wisdom and mercy.",
    "so that you may find comfort in them": "The primary purpose of marriage mentioned here is 'sukun'—tranquility, peace, and emotional rest. Marriage is meant to be a refuge from life's storms, a place of comfort and security. When spouses return to each other, they should find relief from the stresses of the outside world. This peace is a gift from Allah.",
    "And He has placed between you compassion and mercy": "Allah Himself put love (mawaddah) and mercy (rahmah) in the hearts of spouses toward each other. Mawaddah is the passionate love and affection, while rahmah is the gentle mercy and kindness that sustains the relationship, especially as passionate love naturally evolves over time. Young couples often experience more mawaddah, while mature couples rely more on rahmah. Both are divine gifts.",
    "Surely in this are signs for people who reflect": "Those who think deeply about marriage and family relationships will recognize Allah's wisdom and design. The institution of marriage, the natural attraction between spouses, the love that develops, and the children that result—all of these point to a Creator who designed this system with purpose and care."
  },
  22: {
    "And one of His signs is the creation of the heavens and the earth": "The vastness of the universe, the precision of planetary orbits, the beauty of the sky, and the complexity of Earth's ecosystems all point to Allah's creative power. Scientists continue to discover the amazing details of cosmic design, yet they only scratch the surface of what Allah has created.",
    "and the diversity of your languages and colours": "From a single pair of humans, Allah produced humanity with thousands of languages and a beautiful spectrum of skin colors. This diversity is not accidental but intentional. It is meant to be a source of beauty and mutual recognition, not division and racism. The Quran celebrates this diversity as a sign of Allah's creative power. The Prophet (peace be upon him) said that no Arab is superior to a non-Arab except through piety. Our differences make us unique expressions of the same human family.",
    "Surely in this are signs for those of sound knowledge": "People of true knowledge and understanding recognize these signs and glorify Allah because of them. Scholars of language, anthropology, astronomy, and other sciences—when they have sincere hearts—see the hand of the Creator in what they study. Knowledge should lead to recognition of Allah, not arrogance or denial."
  },
  23: {
    "And one of His signs is your sleep by night and by day for rest": "Sleep is a miraculous sign of Allah. During sleep, consciousness departs, the body repairs itself, and the mind processes experiences. Scientists still do not fully understand sleep, yet without it, humans cannot function. Allah designed this period of rest and made the night suitable for it (though sleep can also occur during the day for those who work at night). We take sleep for granted, but it is a daily miracle.",
    "as well as your seeking His bounty in both": "While sleep provides rest, waking hours are for seeking Allah's provision through work and effort. The balance between rest and work is divinely ordained. Whether people work during the day or night shifts, they are seeking from Allah's bounty. All provision ultimately comes from Allah; our work is simply the means by which we receive what He has already decreed for us.",
    "Surely in this are signs for people who listen": "Those who listen attentively to guidance and reflect on their daily experiences will recognize Allah's signs in the cycles of sleep and wakefulness, rest and work. These are not random biological functions but carefully designed systems pointing to a wise Creator."
  },
  24: {
    "And one of His signs is that He shows you lightning, inspiring you with hope and fear": "Lightning evokes two reactions: fear of its destructive power and hope for the rain that usually follows. Travelers might fear being struck, while farmers hope for water for their crops. This single phenomenon produces opposite emotions, yet both lead the thoughtful person to recognize Allah's power. Allah controls forces that can both terrify and benefit us.",
    "And He sends down rain from the sky": "Rain is not random chance but a deliberate act of Allah. He sends it down from the clouds in measured amounts—enough to benefit but not so much as to destroy (unless He wills otherwise as punishment). The water cycle that scientists describe is simply the mechanism through which Allah provides this blessing.",
    "reviving the earth after its death": "Again, this powerful image appears. Barren, cracked, lifeless land suddenly transforms into lush greenery after rain. This annual miracle is so common that we often fail to appreciate it. Yet it is clear evidence of Allah's power to bring life from death—and thus proof that He can resurrect human beings.",
    "Surely in this are signs for people who understand": "Those who use their intellect and reason properly will draw the obvious conclusion: a wise, powerful Creator is behind all of this. The signs are everywhere; what is needed is a mind willing to understand and a heart willing to accept."
  },
  25: {
    "And one of His signs is that the heavens and the earth persist by His command": "The universe functions with perfect order because Allah maintains it. The heavens do not collapse, the earth remains stable for life, and the cosmic laws continue operating—all because of Allah's command. Scientists discover these laws but cannot explain why the universe exists or why it is so orderly. The answer is divine command and maintenance. Without Allah's sustaining power, everything would collapse instantly.",
    "Then when He calls you out of the earth just once, you will instantly come forth": "When Allah commands the resurrection, every human who ever lived will immediately emerge from wherever their remains are—whether buried in graves, scattered in the ocean, or turned to dust. No one will be able to resist or delay for even a moment. Just as the universe obeys His command now, humans will obey His command on that Day. The same power that maintains the cosmos will reassemble every human being."
  },
  26: {
    "And to Him belong all those in the heavens and the earth": "Everything and everyone—angels, humans, jinn, animals, and all creation—belong to Allah as His property. He is the absolute Owner of all existence. Nothing exists independently of Him. This ownership gives Him complete authority over all creation.",
    "all are subject to His Will": "Every being in existence is obedient to Allah in the ultimate sense. Even those who disobey His religious commands still submit to His universal decrees—they cannot escape death, prevent illness, or avoid His ultimate judgment. The word 'qanitun' suggests humility and submission. Everything in creation, willingly or unwillingly, is ultimately under Allah's control."
  },
  27: {
    "And He is the One Who originates the creation then will resurrect it": "This repeats the earlier theme for emphasis. Allah created everything the first time, and He will bring it all back to life for judgment. Both acts—creation and resurrection—are within His power.",
    "which is even easier for Him": "From a human logical perspective, recreating something is easier than creating it originally. If Allah could create us from nothing the first time, how can anyone doubt His ability to resurrect us? However, it is important to note that for Allah, nothing is 'difficult'—He merely says 'Be' and it is. The phrase 'easier for Him' is to help human understanding, not because Allah experiences varying degrees of difficulty.",
    "To Him belong the finest attributes in the heavens and the earth": "Allah has the most perfect, most supreme, and most beautiful attributes. Every good quality exists in Him in its most complete form. His knowledge is perfect, His power is unlimited, His mercy is vast, His wisdom is complete. Nothing in creation can compare to Him, and all positive attributes belong to Him in the highest degree.",
    "And He is the Almighty, All-Wise": "Allah possesses absolute power (Al-Aziz) that cannot be overcome or challenged. Combined with this power is perfect wisdom (Al-Hakeem)—He does everything for good reasons, even when we cannot understand them. His power is never arbitrary, and His wisdom is never weak. This combination of might and wisdom means we can trust His judgments completely."
  },
  28: {
    "He sets forth for you an example drawn from your own lives": "Allah presents a logical argument using something familiar from daily life. The best way to understand complex truths is through relatable examples. Allah uses the social structure that the Arabs knew well to make His point about the absurdity of polytheism.",
    "would you allow some of those bondspeople in your possession to be your equal partners in whatever wealth We have provided you": "Consider this scenario: Would any slave owner willingly make their slaves equal partners in their wealth and property? Would they share ownership equally with those who are under their authority? The obvious answer is no. People do not even share equally with those beneath them in worldly status.",
    "keeping them in mind as you are mindful of your peers?": "Would you fear your slaves and consult them the same way you would fear and respect your equals? Of course not. You treat your equals differently than those under your authority. So here is the powerful conclusion: If you would not make your own slaves equal partners with yourselves, how can you make Allah's creation into partners with Allah? Everything in existence is Allah's creation and under His authority—how then can any created being be elevated to share in His divinity?",
    "This is how We make the signs clear for people who understand": "Allah clarifies His signs through logical reasoning for those willing to use their intellect. The argument against polytheism is not complicated; it simply requires honest reflection. Those who truly think will recognize the absurdity of worshipping anything alongside Allah."
  },
  29: {
    "In fact, the wrongdoers merely follow their desires with no knowledge": "Despite the clear logic against polytheism, the wrongdoers persist in their false beliefs. Why? Not because they have evidence or sound arguments, but simply because they follow their whims and desires. Their worship of idols is based on inherited tradition, personal preferences, and worldly interests—not on any real knowledge or proof. This is the root of most misguidance: following desires instead of truth.",
    "Who then can guide those Allah has left to stray?": "When people persistently choose falsehood over truth and desires over guidance, Allah leaves them in their misguidance as a consequence of their own choices. Once Allah withdraws His guidance from someone due to their stubborn rejection, no one else can guide them. This is not injustice from Allah but a result of their own insistence on going astray.",
    "They will have no helpers": "On the Day of Judgment, these people will find no one to help them, defend them, or save them from the consequences of their choices. The false gods they worshipped will abandon them, and no intercessor will speak on their behalf. They chose to reject Allah's help in this life, so they will have no help in the next."
  },
  30: {
    "So be steadfast in faith in all uprightness O Prophet": "Direct yourself completely and firmly toward the true religion, turning away from all falsehood. The word 'hanif' means one who turns away from misguidance toward the truth, inclining naturally to what is right. The Prophet (peace be upon him) is commanded to be unwavering in his commitment to pure monotheism.",
    "the natural Way of Allah which He has instilled in all people": "This is the concept of 'fitrah'—the natural disposition that Allah created in every human being. Every person is born with an innate recognition of Allah and inclination toward worshipping Him alone. The Prophet (peace be upon him) said: 'Every child is born upon the fitrah, then his parents make him a Jew, Christian, or Magian.' Islam is not a foreign imposition but a return to our original nature.",
    "Let there be no change in this creation of Allah": "This natural disposition should not be corrupted or altered. People should not change their fitrah by adopting false beliefs, worshipping idols, or following man-made religions. The pure monotheistic nature Allah created in us should be preserved and nurtured, not suppressed or distorted.",
    "That is the Straight Way, but most people do not know": "This natural religion of pure monotheism is the correct, balanced, and true path. Unfortunately, most of humanity either does not know this or chooses to ignore it. They follow corrupted traditions, cultural practices, and personal desires instead of returning to the pure faith that their souls naturally recognize."
  },
  31: {
    "O believers! Always turn to Him in repentance": "Constantly return to Allah with sincere repentance. The word 'munibeen' implies repeatedly turning back to Allah, acknowledging mistakes, and seeking His forgiveness. Believers are not perfect; they make mistakes. But they always return to Allah with humility and seek to improve.",
    "be mindful of Him": "Maintain consciousness of Allah (taqwa) in all aspects of life. Be aware that He sees everything you do, knows your thoughts, and will hold you accountable. This awareness should guide your choices and actions.",
    "and establish prayers": "Prayer is the practical manifestation of faith. It is not enough to believe in your heart; you must establish the prayer with its proper times, conditions, and humility. Prayer connects you to Allah five times daily and keeps your faith alive.",
    "And do not be polytheists": "Stay far away from any form of shirk (associating partners with Allah). This includes obvious idol worship and subtle forms like showing off in worship, relying on others instead of Allah, or loving anything more than Allah."
  },
  32: {
    "like those who have divided their faith and split into sects": "Do not be like those who broke apart the unity of true religion. Previous nations received clear guidance but then divided it into competing factions, each taking only what suited them and rejecting the rest. They turned one religion into many conflicting sects, each claiming exclusive truth.",
    "each rejoicing in what they have": "Every sect celebrates its own version of the truth and looks down upon others. They are proud of their particular interpretations and practices while condemning everyone else. This sectarian pride prevents unity and keeps people from the complete truth. The Prophet (peace be upon him) warned his ummah against dividing into such sects, urging them to hold firmly to the Quran and Sunnah as one united community."
  },
  33: {
    "When people are touched with hardship, they cry out to their Lord, turning to Him alone": "Human nature reveals itself in moments of crisis. When people face serious illness, danger, loss, or calamity, they instinctively turn to Allah alone. In those desperate moments, they forget their idols, their superstitions, and their false beliefs. They call only upon Allah because deep down they know only He can truly help. This is the fitrah (natural disposition) emerging even in those who normally deny it.",
    "But as soon as He gives them a taste of His mercy": "However, when Allah responds to their prayers and removes their hardship, granting them relief, health, or prosperity, their attitude quickly changes. The very mercy they begged for becomes a cause of forgetfulness.",
    "a group of them associates others with their Lord in worship": "After being saved by Allah, some people return to their old habits of polytheism. They start attributing their good fortune to idols, saints, lucky charms, or other causes besides Allah. They forget who really answered their prayers. This ingratitude is one of the worst forms of betrayal—being helped by Allah and then turning to others."
  },
  34: {
    "becoming ungrateful for whatever favours We have given them": "Their polytheism is essentially a denial of Allah's blessings. By attributing their good fortune to false gods, they reject the true source of all blessings. Ingratitude is closely linked to shirk because both involve failing to recognize Allah's exclusive role as the Provider and Sustainer.",
    "So enjoy yourselves, for soon you will know": "This is a stern warning disguised as permission. Go ahead and enjoy your temporary pleasures and your false beliefs—but know that a day of reckoning is coming. You will soon discover the reality of your situation when you stand before Allah and your false gods abandon you. This worldly enjoyment is fleeting; the consequences will be eternal."
  },
  35: {
    "Or have We sent down to them an authority which attests to what they associate with Him?": "This is a rhetorical challenge. Has Allah ever sent any scripture, any prophet, any divine proof that supports polytheism? Has any revelation from heaven ever told them to worship idols or saints alongside Allah? The answer is obviously no. Their polytheism has no divine sanction whatsoever. They follow only baseless traditions and desires. If they cannot produce any authority for their beliefs, how can they justify them?"
  },
  36: {
    "If We give people a taste of mercy, they become prideful because of it": "When Allah blesses people with health, wealth, success, or comfort, many become arrogant. Instead of being grateful and humble, they act as if they earned these blessings through their own merit. They become proud, boastful, and forgetful of Allah. Prosperity becomes a test that many fail.",
    "But if they are afflicted with an evil for what their hands have done, they instantly fall into despair": "When hardship strikes—often as a consequence of their own sins and choices—these same people immediately lose hope. They do not see the hardship as a wake-up call or a purification. They do not turn to Allah with patience and prayer. Instead, they despair completely, as if there is no hope and no way out. This emotional instability—arrogance in ease, despair in difficulty—shows a fundamental problem in their relationship with Allah. The believer, by contrast, is grateful in prosperity and patient in hardship, maintaining balance in all circumstances."
  },
  37: {
    "Have they not seen that Allah gives abundant or limited provisions to whoever He wills?": "Wealth and poverty are ultimately in Allah's control. He expands provision for some and restricts it for others according to His wisdom. This is not random, nor is it always based on human effort or worthiness. A believer may be tested with poverty while a disbeliever enjoys wealth—or vice versa. Understanding this helps us avoid judging people by their material status and reminds us to seek provision through lawful means while trusting Allah's decree.",
    "Surely in this are signs for people who believe": "Those with faith recognize Allah's hand in the distribution of wealth. They understand that both abundance and scarcity are tests from Allah. They do not worship wealth or despair over its absence. Instead, they use whatever they have in ways that please Allah."
  },
  38: {
    "So give your close relatives their due": "Family members have rights over your wealth. Before looking far away, take care of those closest to you—parents, siblings, and extended family who may be in need. Maintaining family ties through financial support is highly rewarded in Islam.",
    "as well as the poor and the needy traveller": "Beyond family, extend your generosity to the poor in society and travelers who find themselves stranded without resources. These categories of people deserve support from those whom Allah has blessed with wealth.",
    "That is best for those who seek the pleasure of Allah": "When you give charity seeking only Allah's pleasure—not praise, reputation, or reciprocation—that is the best form of giving. Pure intention transforms ordinary spending into an act of worship that draws you closer to Allah.",
    "and it is they who will be successful": "True success is not measured by how much wealth you accumulate but by how much you give for Allah's sake. Those who spend in charity with sincere intentions are the truly successful ones, both in this world (through Allah's blessings and barakah) and in the Hereafter (through enormous rewards)."
  },
  39: {
    "Whatever loans you give, only seeking interest at the expense of people's wealth will not increase with Allah": "Money given with the expectation of interest (riba) may seem to grow in worldly terms, but it has no value or increase with Allah. In fact, Allah removes all blessings from wealth earned through interest. The one who takes riba thinks they are gaining, but spiritually they are losing. The apparent increase is actually a decrease in the sight of Allah. Interest exploits the needy and creates economic injustice, which is why Islam strictly prohibits it.",
    "But whatever charity you give, only seeking the pleasure of Allah—it is they whose reward will be multiplied": "In contrast, charity given purely for Allah's sake brings enormous multiplication of reward. While interest might double or triple your money, charity can multiply your reward ten times, seven hundred times, or even more according to Allah's generosity. The key is sincerity—giving not for show or worldly benefit but solely to please Allah. This is the true investment that yields eternal returns."
  },
  40: {
    "It is Allah Who created you": "Your very existence is due to Allah alone. He designed you, brought you into being, and gave you form. No idol, saint, or false deity had any part in your creation.",
    "then gives you provisions": "Throughout your life, Allah sustains you with food, water, air, shelter, and countless blessings. Every provision you receive ultimately comes from Him, whether directly or through various means He has created.",
    "then will cause you to die": "At the appointed time, Allah will take your soul. No one can delay death when it arrives, and no one can bring it sooner than decreed. Death is entirely in Allah's hands.",
    "and then will bring you back to life": "After death, Allah will resurrect you for judgment. The One who created you the first time will bring you back again. This cycle of creation, provision, death, and resurrection is entirely controlled by Allah.",
    "Can any of your associate-gods do any of this?": "This is a powerful challenge to polytheists. Can any of the beings or objects you worship create a single human? Can they provide sustenance? Can they give or take life? Can they resurrect the dead? The answer is obviously no. They cannot do any of these things, so why worship them?",
    "Glorified and Exalted is He above what they associate with Him in worship!": "Allah is far above and beyond any comparison to false deities. He is perfect, all-powerful, and unique. The very idea of associating weak, created things with the Almighty Creator is absurd and insulting to His majesty. Glory be to Allah, who has no partner, no equal, and no rival."
  },
  41: {
    "Corruption has spread on land and sea as a result of what people's hands have done": "The world experiences various forms of corruption—environmental destruction, moral decay, injustice, violence, and natural disasters—as a direct consequence of human sin and transgression. When people turn away from Allah's guidance, the effects ripple throughout creation. This corruption is not random but is linked to human actions. The more people sin, the more problems appear in the world around them. This includes both moral corruption (like crime and immorality) and physical corruption (like pollution and ecological damage).",
    "so that Allah may cause them to taste the consequences of some of their deeds": "Allah allows people to experience some results of their wrongdoing in this world. Note that it says 'some'—the full consequences are reserved for the Hereafter. These worldly difficulties are meant to wake people up, to show them that their actions have consequences, and to encourage them to change their ways before it is too late.",
    "and perhaps they might return to the Right Path": "The ultimate purpose of these trials and hardships is to bring people back to Allah. Difficulties are meant to be wake-up calls, not final punishments. Allah, in His mercy, sends warnings before the ultimate punishment, hoping that people will reflect, repent, and return to obedience. Those who understand this wisdom use hardships as opportunities for spiritual growth."
  },
  42: {
    "Say, O Prophet, Travel throughout the land and see what was the end of those destroyed before you": "Again, the Quran invites people to learn from history. Travel to the ruins of ancient civilizations—Petra, the lands of 'Ad and Thamud, Egypt, and others—and observe what happened to those nations. Their impressive structures stand as silent witnesses to divine punishment. They were powerful, wealthy, and advanced, yet they were destroyed because they rejected guidance.",
    "most of them were polytheists": "The primary reason for their destruction was their persistence in polytheism (shirk). They associated partners with Allah despite clear warnings from their prophets. This should be a powerful lesson: no matter how advanced or powerful a civilization becomes, if it is built on the foundation of shirk and disobedience to Allah, it is destined for destruction."
  },
  43: {
    "So be steadfast in the Upright Faith O Prophet": "Devote yourself completely to the true religion—the straight path of Islam. Face the religion with full commitment and do not waver. This command, repeated from earlier, emphasizes the importance of consistency and firmness in faith.",
    "before the coming of a Day from Allah that cannot be averted": "A Day is certainly coming that no one can prevent, delay, or escape. This is the Day of Judgment, decreed by Allah and absolutely inevitable. When that Day comes, there will be no going back, no second chances, and no appeals. The wise person prepares for it now.",
    "On that Day the people will be divided": "Humanity will be split into distinct groups based on their faith and deeds. The unity of humanity in this world will give way to a clear separation between the successful and the failed, the believers and the disbelievers, the inhabitants of Paradise and the dwellers of Hell."
  },
  44: {
    "those who disbelieved will bear the burden of their own disbelief": "Each person is responsible for their own choices. Those who chose to disbelieve will carry the consequences of that choice. They cannot blame anyone else—not their ancestors, not society, not circumstances. Their disbelief is their own burden, and they alone will suffer its consequences.",
    "and those who did good will have prepared for themselves eternal homes": "Those who believed and did righteous deeds are essentially preparing comfortable beds for themselves in Paradise. The Arabic word 'yamhadoon' means to prepare a resting place or to make something smooth and comfortable. Every good deed is like furnishing your eternal home, making your future in the Hereafter better and more comfortable."
  },
  45: {
    "so that He may generously reward those who believe and do good, out of His grace": "Allah will reward the believers not just according to their deeds but with extra generosity from His grace. The reward will far exceed what they actually deserve. This is Allah's favor—He multiplies the reward of good deeds while limiting the punishment for bad deeds to what is justly deserved. His generosity knows no bounds for those who sincerely believe and strive to do good.",
    "He truly does not like the disbelievers": "Allah does not love those who persistently reject Him, deny His signs, and refuse to believe despite clear evidence. His love and special mercy are for the believers. This does not mean Allah is unjust to disbelievers—He gives them chances, provisions, and time to repent—but His special love and eternal rewards are reserved for those who believe."
  },
  46: {
    "And one of His signs is that He sends the winds, ushering in good news of rain": "The winds that bring clouds heavy with rain are among Allah's many signs. When people see certain winds blowing, they anticipate rain and become hopeful. These winds are messengers of good news, heralding Allah's mercy that will revive the land, fill the wells, and nourish the crops.",
    "so that He may give you a taste of His mercy": "Rain is described as Allah's mercy because it brings life, growth, and sustenance. Without rain, the earth would be barren and life would cease. When rain falls, it is a direct manifestation of divine mercy reaching creation.",
    "and that ships may sail by His command": "The wind also enables ships to travel across oceans. Trade, travel, and transportation by sea have been essential throughout human history, and they depend on winds that Allah controls. Modern ships may use engines, but the principle remains—all means of travel ultimately function by Allah's permission.",
    "and that you may seek His bounty": "Wind facilitates commerce and livelihood. Whether through sailing ships carrying trade goods or wind patterns affecting agriculture, people are able to seek their provision. Allah created these systems to enable human economic activity.",
    "and perhaps you will be grateful": "The ultimate purpose of all these blessings is to inspire gratitude. When we recognize that the wind—something we cannot control or create—serves us in so many ways, we should be grateful to the One who controls it. Unfortunately, many people enjoy these blessings without ever thanking the One who provides them."
  },
  47: {
    "Indeed, We sent before you O Prophet messengers, each to their own people": "The Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him) was not the first messenger. Allah sent prophets to every nation throughout history. Each messenger came to his own people with guidance suited to their time and circumstances. This established pattern shows that Allah has always guided humanity.",
    "and they came to them with clear proofs": "Every prophet brought unmistakable evidence of his truthfulness—miracles, logical arguments, pure teachings, and impeccable character. No nation was left without clear guidance. Those who rejected did so despite having clear proof, not because of lack of evidence.",
    "Then We inflicted punishment upon those who persisted in wickedness": "When people stubbornly refused to believe despite clear proofs, divine punishment eventually came upon them. This punishment was not arbitrary but a consequence of their persistent rejection and crimes.",
    "For it is Our duty to help the believers": "Allah has taken upon Himself the obligation to support the believers. This is an incredible promise—the Creator of the universe commits to helping those who believe in Him. While the timing and form of help may vary, the promise itself is certain. Believers may face trials, but ultimate victory and support from Allah are guaranteed."
  },
  48: {
    "It is Allah Who sends the winds, which then stir up vapour, forming clouds": "Allah describes the water cycle in beautiful detail. He sends winds that cause evaporation and gather water vapor into clouds. What scientists describe as meteorological processes are, in reality, actions directed by Allah. He is the one behind every natural phenomenon.",
    "which He then spreads out in the sky or piles up into masses as He wills": "Allah shapes the clouds however He wishes—sometimes spreading them thin across the horizon, sometimes piling them into towering masses. The variety of cloud formations we see are all by His design and will.",
    "from which you see rain come forth": "From within these clouds, rain emerges. The water drops fall to earth, bringing life and sustenance. This familiar process, repeated countless times, is a constant sign of Allah's creative power and mercy.",
    "Then as soon as He causes it to fall on whoever He wills of His servants, they rejoice": "Rain brings immense joy, especially to those who depend on it for their crops and livelihoods. When Allah sends rain to a region, its inhabitants celebrate. This joy is natural and good—it is happiness at receiving Allah's mercy."
  },
  49: {
    "although they had utterly lost hope just before it was sent down to them": "This captures a powerful contrast. Just moments before the rain, the same people who now celebrate were in complete despair. The land was dry, crops were failing, and they saw no way out. Their hopelessness was total. Then Allah sent His mercy, and everything changed. This dramatic shift—from utter despair to overwhelming joy—should teach us never to lose hope in Allah's mercy. Relief can come suddenly and unexpectedly when Allah wills it."
  },
  50: {
    "See then the impact of Allah's mercy: how He gives life to the earth after its death!": "Look with reflection at what happens after rain falls on barren land. Dead, dry earth transforms into lush, green vegetation. Seeds that lay dormant spring to life. Flowers bloom, fruits grow, and the whole landscape is resurrected. This visible transformation is a demonstration of Allah's life-giving power.",
    "Surely That same Creator can raise the dead": "The One who revives dead earth can certainly resurrect dead humans. This is the key lesson. If you can witness the earth's resurrection every year after the rainy season, how can you doubt human resurrection? The same power that brings life to the soil will bring life to the graves. The earth's annual revival is proof and preview of the final resurrection.",
    "For He is Most Capable of everything": "Nothing is beyond Allah's power. He can do all things without effort or limitation. Creating, sustaining, giving life, causing death, and resurrecting—all are easy for Him. Those who doubt the resurrection underestimate Allah's power. He who does the seemingly impossible every season can certainly do what He has promised on the Day of Judgment."
  },
  51: {
    "Then if We send a harsh wind which they see withering their crops, they will definitely deny old favours right after": "Human nature is exposed again. The same people who celebrated Allah's mercy when rain came will quickly turn ungrateful when a harsh wind destroys their crops. Seeing their plants turn yellow and die, they will forget all the previous blessings and complain as if they had never received anything good. This is the tragic inconsistency of the ungrateful heart—quick to forget blessings, quick to complain about trials. The believer, however, remains grateful in good times and patient in bad times, recognizing that both come from Allah's wisdom."
  }
};